'''Suitengu''' (水天宮) is a Shinto shrine located in {{ill|Hokkaido|ja|北海道}} {{ill|Otaru City|ja|小樽市}}. Its former status was that of a {{ill|Local Shrine|ja|郷社}}.

It is sited at a location offering a panoramic view of {{ill|Otaru Port|ja|小樽港}}, and is renowned as one of the famous spots for {{ill|Sakura|ja|サクラ|lt=Cherry Blossoms|lt_ja=桜}} in Otaru City. The steep stairs and slopes descending toward the seaside area of {{ill|Sakaimachi|ja|堺町}} are known as Gaijin-zaka<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.city.otaru.lg.jp/simin/koho/sakamati/1402.html |title=コッフさんと外人坂 前編 |work=おたる坂まち散歩 |publisher={{ill|Otaru City|ja|小樽市}} |accessdate=2016-05-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.city.otaru.lg.jp/simin/koho/sakamati/1403.html |title=コッフさんと外人坂 後編 |work=おたる坂まち散歩 |publisher=小樽市 |accessdate=2016-05-24}}</ref>. A straight road connects the shrine to {{ill|Otaru Park|ja|小樽公園}}, located on the hillside, thereby integrating the surrounding landscape<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=http://www.jila-hokkaido.com/gyouji_/kitanozouensisan/kitanozoen_all/4_otaru/Isan-4(Otaru).pdf |title=小樽公園 |format=PDF |publisher={{ill|Japan Landscape Architecture Society|ja|日本造園学会}} Hokkaido Branch |accessdate=2016-05-12}}</ref>. Within the precincts, there stand monuments such as the {{ill|Ishikawa Takuboku|ja|石川啄木}} poetry monument, the Mitsuya Yōson (みつやようそん) haiku monument, and the {{ill|Kawasomura Bun'ichirō|ja|河邨文一郎}} poetry monument<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=http://otaru-journal.com/2005/10/post-837.php |title=水天宮の啄木歌碑を移設！新たな装いでお目見え！ |date=2005-10-15 |work={{ill|Otaru Journal|ja|小樽ジャーナル}} |publisher=小樽ジャーナル社 |accessdate=2016-05-24}}</ref>.

== Enshrined Deities ==
The shrines sharing the same name as the Suitengu of {{ill|Fukuoka Prefecture|ja|福岡県}} {{ill|Kurume City|ja|久留米市}}, designated as the head shrine, enshrine figures including {{ill|Antoku Emperor|ja|安徳天皇}}, whereas the deities enshrined here are different and do not belong to that lineage{{Sfn|小野|1999|p=103}}.
* {{ill|Mizuhanome|ja|ミヅハノメ|lt=Yatsunahome deity|lt_ja=弥津波能売神}} (Mizuhanome-no-Kami)
* {{ill|Ukemochi|ja|保食神}} (Ukemochi-no-Kami)
* {{ill|Izanagi|ja|伊邪那岐神|lt=Izanagi-no-Kami|lt_ja=伊邪那岐神}} (Izanagi-no-Kami)
* {{ill|Izanami|ja|伊邪那美神|lt=Izanami-no-Kami|lt_ja=伊邪那美神}} (Izanami-no-Kami)

== History ==
* {{ill|1859|ja|1859th year }} ({{ill|Ansei|ja|安政}} 6), established.
* {{ill|1900|ja|1900th year }} ({{ill|Meiji|ja|明治}} 33), upon a petition by the residents, the Ukemochi from the neglected {{ill|Inari Shrine|ja|稲荷神社}} was enshrined alongside.
* {{ill|1919|ja|1919th year }} ({{ill|Taishō|ja|大正}} 8), driven by the sentiments of natives from Shiga Prefecture, the shrine building was reconstructed and the two deities known as Nakuin Nison ({{ill|Izanagi|ja|伊邪那岐神}} and {{ill|Izanami|ja|伊邪那美神}}) from {{ill|Taga Shrine|ja|多賀神社}} were additionally enshrined.
* {{ill|1923|ja|1923rd year }} (Taishō 12), it was elevated to a village shrine and designated as a {{ill|Shinsen Heihaku-ryō Kyōshinjinja|ja|神饌幣*

